</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">After experiencing blunt or penetrating trauma, patients in unstable condition who are more likely to die of uncorrected shock than of incomplete injury repairs undergo emergency limited exploratory laparotomy, which is also known as <i>damage control surgery</i> (DCS). This surgery is part of a series of resuscitation steps, with the goal of stabilizing the patient’s condition, with rapid surgical control of hemorrhage followed by supportive measures in the intensive care unit before definitive repair of injuries. These patients often are imaged with multidetector CT within 24–48 hours of the initial surgery. Knowledge of this treatment plan is critical to CT interpretation, because there are anatomic derangements and foreign bodies that would not be present in patients undergoing surgery for other reasons. Patients may have injuries beyond the surgical field that are only identified at imaging, which can alter the care plan. Abnormalities related to the resuscitation period such as the CT hypoperfusion complex and ongoing hemorrhage can be recognized at CT. Familiarity with these imaging and clinical findings is important, because they can be seen not only in trauma patients after DCS but also in other patients in the critical care setting. The interpretation of imaging studies can be helped by an understanding of the diagnostic challenges of grading organ injuries with surgical materials in place and the awareness of potential artifacts on images in these patients.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2019</div><div role="paragraph">See discussion on this article by <a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/doi/full/10.1148/rg.2019190056">LeBedis</a>.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180153">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180153">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig1.jpeg" height="1324" width="1793" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Flowchart shows the vicious bloody cycle of the trauma patient in unstable condition, in whom injuries that cause large-volume blood loss result in a cycle of coagulopathy, hypothermia, and acidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig2.jpeg" height="2193" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Flowchart shows steps for damage control in trauma patients in unstable condition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig3a.jpeg" height="1485" width="1797" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Typical appearance of laparotomy pads. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced CT images (soft-tissue window) after DCS show the bubbly heterogeneous appearance of laparotomy pads (arrows) with radiopaque bands (arrowheads) along the liver hilum and in the central mesentery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image (bone window) shows a reduction in streak artifacts, which allows better delineation of the radiopaque marker in the pad (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig3b.jpeg" height="1467" width="1321" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Typical appearance of laparotomy pads. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced CT images (soft-tissue window) after DCS show the bubbly heterogeneous appearance of laparotomy pads (arrows) with radiopaque bands (arrowheads) along the liver hilum and in the central mesentery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image (bone window) shows a reduction in streak artifacts, which allows better delineation of the radiopaque marker in the pad (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig3c.jpeg" height="1462" width="1825" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Typical appearance of laparotomy pads. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced CT images (soft-tissue window) after DCS show the bubbly heterogeneous appearance of laparotomy pads (arrows) with radiopaque bands (arrowheads) along the liver hilum and in the central mesentery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image (bone window) shows a reduction in streak artifacts, which allows better delineation of the radiopaque marker in the pad (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig4.jpeg" height="1805" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Frontal localizer image for CT. This radiograph-equivalent image in a 17-year-old adolescent boy who underwent DCS for hemodynamic instability after a motor vehicle collision is helpful to count laparotomy pads (arrows) and to differentiate this packing material from drains (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig5.jpeg" height="1803" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Small-bowel discontinuity in a 40-year-old man after emergency surgery for a penetrating abdominal injury. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows blind-ending small-bowel segments with dense suture material at the closed ends (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig6a.jpeg" height="1632" width="1819" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Vacuum-assisted pressure dressing in a 22-year-old man who underwent emergency exploratory laparotomy after a rollover motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image (soft-tissue window) shows the open ventral abdominal wall with bowel protrusion (dotted circle). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> CT images (lung window) show the overlying dressing material with drains for suction (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig6b.jpeg" height="1635" width="1725" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Vacuum-assisted pressure dressing in a 22-year-old man who underwent emergency exploratory laparotomy after a rollover motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image (soft-tissue window) shows the open ventral abdominal wall with bowel protrusion (dotted circle). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> CT images (lung window) show the overlying dressing material with drains for suction (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig6c.jpeg" height="2336" width="1401" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Vacuum-assisted pressure dressing in a 22-year-old man who underwent emergency exploratory laparotomy after a rollover motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image (soft-tissue window) shows the open ventral abdominal wall with bowel protrusion (dotted circle). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> CT images (lung window) show the overlying dressing material with drains for suction (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig7a.jpeg" height="2248" width="1397" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Gunshot wound to the right flank in a 47-year-old man with hypotension and tachycardia who underwent emergency right nephrectomy, partial colectomy, and splenectomy. <b>(a)</b> CT localizer image shows perihepatic, right lower quadrant, and splenectomy bed laparotomy pads (arrows). Ballistic fragments project at the L2–L3 level and in the right abdomen (dashed circle). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows packing material (<b>*</b>) around the liver and paracolic gutters. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image (lung window) shows ballistic fragment in the spinal canal, an open midline incision (arrow), and free air (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig7b.jpeg" height="1342" width="1896" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Gunshot wound to the right flank in a 47-year-old man with hypotension and tachycardia who underwent emergency right nephrectomy, partial colectomy, and splenectomy. <b>(a)</b> CT localizer image shows perihepatic, right lower quadrant, and splenectomy bed laparotomy pads (arrows). Ballistic fragments project at the L2–L3 level and in the right abdomen (dashed circle). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows packing material (<b>*</b>) around the liver and paracolic gutters. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image (lung window) shows ballistic fragment in the spinal canal, an open midline incision (arrow), and free air (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig7c.jpeg" height="1339" width="1848" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Gunshot wound to the right flank in a 47-year-old man with hypotension and tachycardia who underwent emergency right nephrectomy, partial colectomy, and splenectomy. <b>(a)</b> CT localizer image shows perihepatic, right lower quadrant, and splenectomy bed laparotomy pads (arrows). Ballistic fragments project at the L2–L3 level and in the right abdomen (dashed circle). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows packing material (<b>*</b>) around the liver and paracolic gutters. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image (lung window) shows ballistic fragment in the spinal canal, an open midline incision (arrow), and free air (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig8a.jpeg" height="2039" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Shotgun pellets in a 35-year-old man after DCS for a gunshot injury. <b>(a)</b> CT localizer image shows numerous high-attenuating round shotgun pellets. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the pellets in the abdominal wall soft tissues, liver (circle), and pancreas (arrow). Note the linear streak artifact surrounding each fragment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig8b.jpeg" height="1317" width="1698" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Shotgun pellets in a 35-year-old man after DCS for a gunshot injury. <b>(a)</b> CT localizer image shows numerous high-attenuating round shotgun pellets. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the pellets in the abdominal wall soft tissues, liver (circle), and pancreas (arrow). Note the linear streak artifact surrounding each fragment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig9.jpeg" height="1367" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Embedded ballistic material with hepatic injury. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image (soft-tissue window) in a 31-year-old man after DCS for a gunshot injury shows irregular hypointensity in the area of hepatorrhaphy and laceration in the right lobe (arrows). The ballistic fragment (oval) is lodged in the spinal canal and causes streak artifacts (arrows) through the liver and stomach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig10.jpeg" height="1075" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. CT findings of hypovolemia in a 65-year-old woman who was unresponsive and hypotensive after a high-speed motor vehicle collision. Axial CT image shows a flattened inferior vena cava (curved arrow) and a hyperenhancing left adrenal gland. A suspected pancreatic injury with fluid around the head and pancreaticoduodenal groove (straight arrows) was not confirmed, because the patient died.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig11a.jpeg" height="1615" width="1381" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Shock liver after exploratory laparotomy in a 13-year-old boy with cardiac arrest who was injured in a motor vehicle collision (dirt bike vs dump truck). <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show patchy heterogeneous hepatic enhancement and a small amount of free fluid in the splenectomy bed (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows gallbladder wall edema and slit-like flattening of the inferior vena cava (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig11b.jpeg" height="977" width="1636" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Shock liver after exploratory laparotomy in a 13-year-old boy with cardiac arrest who was injured in a motor vehicle collision (dirt bike vs dump truck). <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show patchy heterogeneous hepatic enhancement and a small amount of free fluid in the splenectomy bed (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows gallbladder wall edema and slit-like flattening of the inferior vena cava (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig11c.jpeg" height="978" width="1515" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Shock liver after exploratory laparotomy in a 13-year-old boy with cardiac arrest who was injured in a motor vehicle collision (dirt bike vs dump truck). <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show patchy heterogeneous hepatic enhancement and a small amount of free fluid in the splenectomy bed (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows gallbladder wall edema and slit-like flattening of the inferior vena cava (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig12a.jpeg" height="1283" width="1692" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. CT hypoperfusion complex after DCS with splenectomy and left chest tube placement in a 37-year-old man with a left thoracoabdominal wound. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows small-bowel wall thickening and mucosal hyperenhancement with flattening of the inferior vena cava (arrowhead) at the level of the renal veins. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows free air along the liver and diffuse bowel wall hyperemia and thickening. A drain (arrow) lies against the posterior left hepatic lobe.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig12b.jpeg" height="1281" width="1450" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. CT hypoperfusion complex after DCS with splenectomy and left chest tube placement in a 37-year-old man with a left thoracoabdominal wound. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows small-bowel wall thickening and mucosal hyperenhancement with flattening of the inferior vena cava (arrowhead) at the level of the renal veins. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows free air along the liver and diffuse bowel wall hyperemia and thickening. A drain (arrow) lies against the posterior left hepatic lobe.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig13a.jpeg" height="1766" width="1178" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. CT hypoperfusion complex after DCS with splenectomy for an actively bleeding shattered spleen in a 22-year-old man who was injured in a motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows diffuse small-bowel wall thickening with hyperenhancement and packing material in the left upper quadrant splenectomy bed (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows hyperenhancing adrenal glands (circles), hyperenhancing small bowel protruding through the open abdominal incision, and packing material in the left upper quadrant (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig13b.jpeg" height="1767" width="1768" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. CT hypoperfusion complex after DCS with splenectomy for an actively bleeding shattered spleen in a 22-year-old man who was injured in a motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows diffuse small-bowel wall thickening with hyperenhancement and packing material in the left upper quadrant splenectomy bed (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows hyperenhancing adrenal glands (circles), hyperenhancing small bowel protruding through the open abdominal incision, and packing material in the left upper quadrant (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig14a.jpeg" height="1223" width="1427" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Unsuspected splenic pseudoaneurysm in a 49-year-old man after thoracic exploration for penetrating ballistic chest trauma. <b>(a)</b> Chest CT localizer image shows numerous shotgun pellets and packing material in the chest wall wound and left upper quadrant. The left lower lobe is completely collapsed, with a thoracotomy tube in the left chest. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced chest CT images including the upper abdomen show a small perisplenic hematoma (arrow in <b>b</b>), ballistic fragment in the spleen, and inferior splenic pseudoaneurysm (oval in <b>c</b>). Note the external device creating streak artifact lines in the liver. The patient was taken back to the operating room for splenectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig14b.jpeg" height="1223" width="1724" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Unsuspected splenic pseudoaneurysm in a 49-year-old man after thoracic exploration for penetrating ballistic chest trauma. <b>(a)</b> Chest CT localizer image shows numerous shotgun pellets and packing material in the chest wall wound and left upper quadrant. The left lower lobe is completely collapsed, with a thoracotomy tube in the left chest. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced chest CT images including the upper abdomen show a small perisplenic hematoma (arrow in <b>b</b>), ballistic fragment in the spleen, and inferior splenic pseudoaneurysm (oval in <b>c</b>). Note the external device creating streak artifact lines in the liver. The patient was taken back to the operating room for splenectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig14c.jpeg" height="1443" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Unsuspected splenic pseudoaneurysm in a 49-year-old man after thoracic exploration for penetrating ballistic chest trauma. <b>(a)</b> Chest CT localizer image shows numerous shotgun pellets and packing material in the chest wall wound and left upper quadrant. The left lower lobe is completely collapsed, with a thoracotomy tube in the left chest. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced chest CT images including the upper abdomen show a small perisplenic hematoma (arrow in <b>b</b>), ballistic fragment in the spleen, and inferior splenic pseudoaneurysm (oval in <b>c</b>). Note the external device creating streak artifact lines in the liver. The patient was taken back to the operating room for splenectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig15.jpeg" height="1696" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Active hepatic bleeding in a 27- year-old man with a grade IV liver laceration after exploratory laparotomy for a gunshot wound. Contrast-enhanced axial CT image shows a hypoenhancing laceration in hepatic segment VI (arrowhead) with active contrast material extravasation beyond the liver capsule into the subcutaneous tissues (circle). There is an adjacent grade IV renal injury to the right kidney, with laceration extending to the hilum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig16a.jpeg" height="1547" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Mesenteric bleeding in a 17-year-old adolescent boy who underwent emergency exploratory laparotomy (intraoperative findings of a grade II liver laceration, mesenteric hematoma, and cecal serosal injury) after a motor vehicle collision. Immediate postoperative axial contrast-enhanced CT images show hyperenhancing active contrast material extravasation from the mesentery collecting in the abdominal mesenteric packing material (arrow) despite exploration and packing, and hemorrhagic hyperenhancing fluid in the paracolic gutters (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig16b.jpeg" height="1547" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Mesenteric bleeding in a 17-year-old adolescent boy who underwent emergency exploratory laparotomy (intraoperative findings of a grade II liver laceration, mesenteric hematoma, and cecal serosal injury) after a motor vehicle collision. Immediate postoperative axial contrast-enhanced CT images show hyperenhancing active contrast material extravasation from the mesentery collecting in the abdominal mesenteric packing material (arrow) despite exploration and packing, and hemorrhagic hyperenhancing fluid in the paracolic gutters (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig17a.jpeg" height="1486" width="1493" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Images acquired after exploratory laparotomy in a 22-year-old man who was involved in a rollover motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Retrograde urethrogram obtained in the operating room for blood at the urethral meatus shows posterior urethral disruption with extraperitoneal contrast material extravasation. <b>(b, c)</b> Immediate postoperative axial CT images show multiple pelvic fractures (black arrow) including the left acetabulum <b>(b)</b> and the right L5 pedicle <b>(c)</b>. The open abdominal incision with bowel protrusion shows overlying vacuum-assisted dressing (white arrow in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig17b.jpeg" height="1480" width="1674" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Images acquired after exploratory laparotomy in a 22-year-old man who was involved in a rollover motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Retrograde urethrogram obtained in the operating room for blood at the urethral meatus shows posterior urethral disruption with extraperitoneal contrast material extravasation. <b>(b, c)</b> Immediate postoperative axial CT images show multiple pelvic fractures (black arrow) including the left acetabulum <b>(b)</b> and the right L5 pedicle <b>(c)</b>. The open abdominal incision with bowel protrusion shows overlying vacuum-assisted dressing (white arrow in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig17c.jpeg" height="1480" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Images acquired after exploratory laparotomy in a 22-year-old man who was involved in a rollover motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Retrograde urethrogram obtained in the operating room for blood at the urethral meatus shows posterior urethral disruption with extraperitoneal contrast material extravasation. <b>(b, c)</b> Immediate postoperative axial CT images show multiple pelvic fractures (black arrow) including the left acetabulum <b>(b)</b> and the right L5 pedicle <b>(c)</b>. The open abdominal incision with bowel protrusion shows overlying vacuum-assisted dressing (white arrow in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig18a.jpeg" height="1755" width="1848" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Active hemorrhage in a 32-year-old man who was ejected from a motorcycle and had continued hypotension after DCS. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows asymmetric hemorrhagic fluid and edema in the left abdominal wall, with focal active contrast material extravasation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Catheter angiogram shows the bleeding artery and the site treated with an embolization coil via the left L3 lumbar artery (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig18b.jpeg" height="1754" width="1302" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Active hemorrhage in a 32-year-old man who was ejected from a motorcycle and had continued hypotension after DCS. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows asymmetric hemorrhagic fluid and edema in the left abdominal wall, with focal active contrast material extravasation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Catheter angiogram shows the bleeding artery and the site treated with an embolization coil via the left L3 lumbar artery (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig19a.jpeg" height="1369" width="1376" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Delayed hernia through a diaphragmatic injury in a 28-year-old man after he sustained a knife stab wound. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image obtained after knife removal at the time of initial injury shows a small defect in the left diaphragm (arrow), which was managed conservatively. <b>(b)</b> CT image obtained 3 years later when the patient presented with severe epigastric and chest pain shows herniation of the stomach (arrow) through the diaphragmatic defect.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig19b.jpeg" height="1369" width="1772" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Delayed hernia through a diaphragmatic injury in a 28-year-old man after he sustained a knife stab wound. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image obtained after knife removal at the time of initial injury shows a small defect in the left diaphragm (arrow), which was managed conservatively. <b>(b)</b> CT image obtained 3 years later when the patient presented with severe epigastric and chest pain shows herniation of the stomach (arrow) through the diaphragmatic defect.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig20.jpeg" height="1087" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Artifact from external devices. Axial CT image in a 21-year-old man who was involved in a motor vehicle collision shows an external metallic object (straight white arrow) along the left lateral thoracoabdominal wall that creates hypoattenuating bands (black arrows) in the liver that mimic lacerations. A small laceration is present in the posterior right lobe (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig21.jpeg" height="1568" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. CT artifact from an internal foreign body. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 24-year-old man who sustained a ballistic injury to the left thigh shows the ballistic fragment (dashed circle) in the thigh soft tissues with a markedly hypoenhancing streak artifact (arrows) across the femoral vessels and thigh soft tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig22a.jpeg" height="1673" width="1384" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Pseudofractures in a 43-year-old man who was in a motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT reconstruction (bone window) shows several step-off cortical irregularities (arrows) which are suspicious for sternal fractures; however, the similar irregularity along the skin surface confirms that they are motion artifacts. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT localizer image can be helpful to assess for fractures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180153/asset/images/large/rg.2019180153.fig22b.jpeg" height="1673" width="1571" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Pseudofractures in a 43-year-old man who was in a motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT reconstruction (bone window) shows several step-off cortical irregularities (arrows) which are suspicious for sternal fractures; however, the similar irregularity along the skin surface confirms that they are motion artifacts. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT localizer image can be helpful to assess for fractures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180153&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Web-based injury statistics query and reporting system. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/injury/wisqars/facts.html">https://www.cdc.gov/injury/wisqars/facts.html</a>. Published 2018. Accessed July 24, 2018.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Web-based+injury+statistics+query+and+reporting+system.+Centers+for+Disease+Control+and+Prevention+%28CDC%29.+https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cdc.gov%2Finjury%2Fwisqars%2Ffacts.html.+Published+2018.+Accessed+July+24%2C+2018.">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Brown CVR, Rix K, Klein AL, et al. A comprehensive investigation of comorbidities, mechanisms, injury patterns, and outcomes in geriatric blunt trauma patients. <em>Am Surg</em> 2016;82(11):1055–1062.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1177/000313481608201119">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28206931/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=A+comprehensive+investigation+of+comorbidities%2C+mechanisms%2C+injury+patterns%2C+and+outcomes+in+geriatric+blunt+trauma+patients&amp;author=CVR+Brown&amp;author=K+Rix&amp;author=AL+Klein&amp;publication_year=2016&amp;journal=Am+Surg&amp;pages=1055-1062&amp;doi=10.1177%2F000313481608201119&amp;pmid=28206931">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Tyburski JG, Wilson RF, Dente C, Steffes C, Carlin AM. Factors affecting mortality rates in patients with abdominal vascular injuries. <em>J Trauma</em> 2001;50(6):1020–1026.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/00005373-200106000-00008">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11426115/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Factors+affecting+mortality+rates+in+patients+with+abdominal+vascular+injuries&amp;author=JG+Tyburski&amp;author=RF+Wilson&amp;author=C+Dente&amp;author=C+Steffes&amp;author=AM+Carlin&amp;publication_year=2001&amp;journal=J+Trauma&amp;pages=1020-1026&amp;doi=10.1097%2F00005373-200106000-00008&amp;pmid=11426115">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Harvin JA, Maxim T, Inaba K, et al. Mortality after emergent trauma laparotomy: a multicenter, retrospective study. <em>J Trauma Acute Care Surg</em> 2017;83(3):464–468.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/TA.0000000000001619">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28598906/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Mortality+after+emergent+trauma+laparotomy%3A+a+multicenter%2C+retrospective+study&amp;author=JA+Harvin&amp;author=T+Maxim&amp;author=K+Inaba&amp;publication_year=2017&amp;journal=J+Trauma+Acute+Care+Surg&amp;pages=464-468&amp;doi=10.1097%2FTA.0000000000001619&amp;pmid=28598906">G